<LP>
   RISING OIL PRICES will cut the nation's already sluggish
economic growth by half but won't cause a recession, Treasury
Secretary Brady said. He again called on the Fed to ease
credit, and said those in Congress who view the current
problems as reasons to put off cutting the budget deficit are
"dead wrong."
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   The likelihood of a rebound in corporate profits in the
second half all but evaporated with Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait. The oil crisis makes it more likely that profits will
continue to decline until sometime in 1991.
   ---
   Producer prices fell 0.1% in July, suggesting that
inflationary pressures were easing before the recent jump in
oil prices. The report will make it easier for the Fed to
push down interest rates, although higher oil prices might
prevent it from lowering rates enough to avoid a recession.
   ---
   Thousands of asbestos cases could be dealt with under an
unusual plan approved by federal judges across the U.S. The
move is intended to pressure the defendants to either agree
to a consolidated nationwide settlement or go to trial in a
class-action suit.
   ---
   Robert Campeau was removed as chief executive of Campeau
Corp. and replaced by representatives of the troubled firm's
major creditors.
   ---
   Tokyo stock prices sank Monday morning on heavy selling by
arbitragers. At midday, the Nikkei index was down 763.12
points, or 2.8%.
   ---
   Chase Manhattan plans to offer a severance program to
several thousand U.S. employees as part of its effort to trim
costs by $300 million.
   ---
   Pic 'N' Save deflected a proxy fight by agreeing to name
three people to its board, widen a buy-back and drop
anti-takeover measures.
   ---
   Donald Trump intends to hire First Boston Corp. to
organize a restructuring of $1.3 billion in casino bonds,
according to several individuals.
   ---
   GM signaled that it plans broad price increases on most of
its 1991 cars and trucks, but will continue to offer
discounts if buyers balk.
   ---
   First Executive Corp. said Deloitte &amp; Touche has decided
not to continue as its auditor. The insurance firm earlier
this year reported an $859 million write-down of its
junk-bond portfolio.
   ---
   Chrysler was ordered to pay $7.6 million for mail fraud in
connection with the sale of about 30 previously wrecked cars
as new vehicles.
   ---
   UPS agreed with the Teamsters union to keep negotiating on
a new labor pact even if employees reject the
delivery-service firm's latest offer.
   ---
   Fuji Securities is adding personnel to its U.S. government
securities trading operation, a surprise in an industry that
has been devastated by losses.
   ---
   Homestead Financial posted a surprising $30.2 million
second-quarter loss, reflecting loss reserves tied to the
California real estate market.
   ---
   Southmark emerged from Chapter 11 reorganization and began
distributions to creditors and shareholders.
